The invention will be more clearly understood and other features and advantages of this invention will appear with the aid of the description below and of the appended drawings in which:


FIG. 1 illustrates an example of an optical architecture of a so-called second-generation camera with a re-imager, according to the prior art;


FIG. 2a shows a general optical architecture of a wide-field (WF) camera, according to the invention;


FIG. 2b shows a general optical architecture of a narrow-field (NF) camera, according to the invention;


FIG. 3a shows the behaviour of the modulation transfer function (MTF) of the optical architecture of a camera, according to the prior art;


FIG. 3b shows the behaviour of the modulation transfer function (MTF) of the optical architecture of a camera, according to the invention;


FIG. 4a shows the reduction in the structure flux due to the conjugating mirror of a camera (in the case of an elementary detector located at the centre of the detector), according to the invention;


FIG. 4b shows the reduction in the structure flux due to the conjugating mirror of a camera (in the case of an elementary detector located at the edge of the detector), according to the invention;


FIG. 5a illustrates the hippodrome shape of the cold stop of the detector of a camera, according to the prior art;


FIG. 5b illustrates the optimized shape of the cold stop of the detector of a camera, according to the invention;


FIG. 6 illustrates the variations in the photometric inefficiency along the detector, according to various shapes of the cold stop;


FIG. 7a illustrates the variations in the image of the entrance pupil on the front lens of the front afocal during scanning when the exit pupil of the front afocal is located on the image of the stop;


FIG. 7b illustrates the variations in the image of the entrance pupil on the front lens of the front afocal during scanning, when the exit pupil of the front afocal is located between the scanner and stop;


FIG. 7c illustrates the variations in the image of the entrance pupil on the front lens of the front afocal during scanning, when the exit pupil of the front afocal is located on the scanner;


FIG. 8 illustrates the long afocal of the optical architecture of a camera, according to the prior art;


FIG. 9 illustrates the short afocal of the optical architecture of a camera, according to the invention;


FIG. 10 shows an optical architecture of the camera in its foldable version, according to the invention.
